  "text": "The Prometheus TSDB write-ahead log (WAL) implementation spans multiple Go source files in the prometheus/prometheus repository, organized around segment management, record encoding/decoding, and WAL replay. **Core WAL Implementation (tsdb/wlog/):** The `wlog.go` file contains the main WL (Write Log) type that manages WAL segment creation and rotation. Key functions include `CreateSegment()` and `OpenWriteSegment()` for segment creation, `NextSegment()` and `NextSegmentSync()` for segment rotation, and the `Repair()` method for handling corrupted segments. The WL type uses a page-based buffering system (32KB pages) with automatic segment rotation when records would exceed segment boundaries, ensuring no records cross segment boundaries. Segments are stored as numbered files (00000000, 00000001, etc.) and can be efficiently truncated via the `Truncate()` method. **Record Encoding (tsdb/record/record.go):** The record package defines the WAL record format with separate types for different data: RefSeries (series definitions), RefSample (float samples), RefMetadata (metric metadata), RefExemplar (exemplars), RefHistogramSample (histogram samples), and RefFloatHistogramSample (float histogram samples). The Encoder type provides methods for encoding each record type (`Series()`, `Samples()`, `Metadata()`, `Tombstones()`, `HistogramSamples()`, etc.) using a binary format with delta encoding for timestamps and reference numbers. The Decoder type provides corresponding decoding methods and can identify record types. **Checkpoint Creation (tsdb/wlog/checkpoint.go):** The `Checkpoint()` function creates compacted checkpoints of WAL segments to truncate old WAL data. It reads from a specified range of segments, filters out old data (based on timestamp and series filters), and writes a new checkpoint directory containing the relevant records in the same WAL format. The `LastCheckpoint()` function retrieves the most recent checkpoint, and `DeleteCheckpoints()` removes old checkpoints. Checkpoints are stored in directories named checkpoint.XXXXXXXX. **WAL Reading (tsdb/wlog/reader.go and live_reader.go):** The Reader type in reader.go reads complete WAL records from a fully written segment, reconstructing records that may span pages. The LiveReader type in live_reader.go reads WAL records while they are still being written, supporting streaming reading from active segments. Both implement record validation with CRC32 checksums and decompression for records compressed with Snappy or Zstd. **WAL Repair (tsdb/wlog/wlog.go):** The `Repair()` method handles corrupted segments by identifying the corruption point, deleting all segments after the corrupted one, and replaying all valid records from the corrupted segment up to the corruption offset into a new clean segment. This preserves all uncorrupted data while discarding the corrupted portion. **WAL Integration with Head (tsdb/head_wal.go):** The `loadWAL()` function replays WAL records into the in-memory head database during startup, restoring all series, samples, tombstones, exemplars, and metadata. It uses concurrent workers to process WAL records for different series in parallel. The `loadWBL()` function handles out-of-order write-ahead logs for out-of-order samples. **WAL Watching (tsdb/wlog/watcher.go):** The Watcher type monitors WAL segments and forwards records to external systems (like remote write endpoints), using the LiveReader to read records as they're written. It integrates with the remote write system to send WAL data reliably.\n\nThe implementation emphasizes crash-safety through page-based writes, CRC32 validation, and segment-level atomicity, allowing safe recovery from power loss or corruption at any point in the WAL."
